To save data in LocalStorage, use the `setItem()` method. This method takes two parameters: a key (string) and a value (any type). Here's an example of how to set a key-value pair:

```javascript
localStorage.setItem('key', 'value');
```

To read data from LocalStorage, use the `getItem()` method. This method also takes one parameter: a key (string). It returns the value associated with that key if it exists in the storage. If the key does not exist, it will return null or undefined. Here's an example of how to get a value by its key:

```javascript
var storedValue = localStorage.getItem('key');
if (storedValue !== null) {
// The key exists and has a non-null value
} else {
// The key does not exist or the value is null
}
```

You can also use `localStorage.getItem()` to get an array of all stored items, where each item is an object with keys representing the original property names and values being their corresponding storage values:

```javascript
var storedItems = localStorage.getItem(''); // Get all stored items by default key (empty string)
if (!storedItems) {
// No data has been saved in LocalStorage yet
} else {
for (let item of storedItems) {
console.log('Key:', item.key, 'Value:', item.value); // Log each key-value pair
}
}
```
